    h3 UNIVERSALITY OF NAND GATE
    p All basic logic gates can be obtained from NAND gates and that is why it is called a universal logic gate.
    p.
        Fig-16(a) shows how we tie inputs of NAND gate together to get a NOT gate that has only One input. If input 
        is 0, then both the inputs to NAND gate are 0. Following NAND gate truth table, we see output now is 1. 
        Similarly, if input is 1, both the inputs to NAND gate are 1 that gives output 0. Therefore, output of circuit 
        is complement of its input and thus gives NOT operation.
    p.
        Fig-16(b) shows how we get AND circuit using only NAND gates. The second NAND gate performs as a NOT gate and 
        inverts the NAND logic of first NAND gate to AND logic.
    p.
        To obtain OR logic using NAND gate, we draw circuit diagram as shown in Fig-16(c). This circuit has NAND gate 
        at output and thus, inverts the output of previous circuit, from NOR to OR.
    img(src='/public/images/elec-comm/01/lab02/16a.png')
    p.center Fig.-16(a): NOT gate using NAND gate
    img(src='/public/images/elec-comm/01/lab02/16b.png')
    p.center Fig.-16(b): AND gate using NAND gate
    img(src='/public/images/elec-comm/01/lab02/16c.png')
    p.center Fig.-16(c): OR gate using NAND gate
    br
    h3 2.) The NOR Gate 
    p.
        It is a logic circuit in which OR gate is followed by a NOT gate. The output of NOR gate is LOW if any of the 
        inputs are HIGH. Its symbol is an OR gate with a small circle on the output (Fig-17). The small circle 
        represents inversion. Boolean expression for NOR gate is as follows:
    p $$ Y = \neg{(A+B)}$$
    img(src='/public/images/elec-comm/01/lab02/nor-gate-schema.png')
    p.center Fig.-17: Symbol of 2-input NOR gate
    br
    include gatetables/norgate-quad.pug 
    br
